76561198030762242,Not Recommended,426330,24804417,"Posted: 9 August, 2016",all,FirestormMk3,"This is the only story bad this company I've felt a need to not reccomend, as most of their other work is fantastic.In this game, you suddenly find yourself forced to be the CEO of a company that sells human augmentation fueled by super science or occult magic.  You make major corporate decesions and choose what staff to hire and what kinds of tech to develop with the benefit that you can have any augmentations developed for free.  In the background is a mystery involving extra-dimensional beings and the disappearance of the former CEO, which escolates to involve no less than the fate of the world itself.Unfortunatley, without wishing to give any spoilers, there are, practically speaking, only two endings for this story, which is a divergence from the many combinations involved in this company's other works.  If you don't make choices that perfectly fit in the narrative of the two endings the writer wants the game actually has a time loop that dumps you back at the start of the story, convienently giving the player character amnesia so you can't have new decisions from foreknowledge, and tells you make all the same choices again, until you pick the ones we want you to.  This defeats the purpose of the story having any player agency whatsoever.  I was very disappointed and after my third time loop the shoehorned choices became very clear and I abandoned the game."
76561197994405912,Not Recommended,426330,20024410,"Posted: 27 December, 2015",all,Wintery,"The good:  Amazingly realized world, great writing.  If you're the kind of person that cares whether a game accomodates non-binary gender pronouns and the like then you'll find they've taken every measure for sensitivity's sake.  The power fantasy of running, lets be honest here Massive Dynamics from Fringe, is great fun.The Bad:  Unlike most of their games there appears to be one path to win, or at least a narrower set of them than the usual.    At points it becomes less-than-realistic.  There is way more randomness than many Choice of Games entries with your resources which are what determines how much you can do and thus how much you can make.  So a bit of bad luck or one bad decision quickly snowballs into an unwinnable playthrough.The Bottom Line:  A great game, but not as superlatively awesome as others from this publisher.  The skill development system (which normally is a glorified decision tree system, if you've skilled up in a given area more than X times then you can sweet-talk the guard if not... he kicks your butt) is reused to provide more freeform options.  It's a shame that they never really go anywhere interesting with it because it boils down to ""have you checked enough boxes to win?""  Relies a bit much on guessing, the results of actions are not always logically connected to the input: a fatal flaw in a text-based game like this!  This is especially apparent in the first act.  Also, a lot of threads like the Romance options seem shoehorned in so they can say ""has X romances!"" on the promo blurb and have no bearing on gameplay in a significant way.  In one playthrough I was gay, in the next a lesbian, and the lesbian romance option was slightly more fleshed out (ooh, controversial!) because they went on vacation with me.  But beyond a few more scenes and a chance to♥♥♥♥♥♥off my partner by ignoring her wishes and engaging in corporate skulduggery she asked me not to, nothing of consequences was gained or loss.Buy this if you like:  Power fantasies, reading unique novels and genres, streamlined management sims"
